I‚Äôm asked a lot of the time when I‚Äôm studying why do I take hand written summaries sometimes and charts/outlines other times. To be honest, I get bored when studying and sometimes drawing things out really helps to stimulate my brain and keep me focused on what I‚Äôm studying.

However studying for NBEO Part I has changed this for me. I spent a lot of time drawing things out for subjects like anatomy but quickly realized how time consuming that can become.

Something I‚Äôve found to work for me is to draw things out when I‚Äôm reviewing for a second time to summarize the highlights or when I‚Äôm studying topics that aren‚Äôt sticking. Like the actions of EOMs.. I know this topic is covered in several sections and it‚Äôs important to know it that like the back of my hand. So I‚Äôve made a quick summary sheet to have when I‚Äôm reviewing.

Have you guys heard of Focus Sprints? I've recently learned about this phrase from one of Matthew Encina's videos (@matthewencina @thefuturishere). It's simply taking 90 minutes to cut off all distractions, placing everything on do not disturb mode and setting a timer for 90 minutes.

Create a goal that you want to get done during this sprint and go. This time is set aside for focus and getting intense work done.

I've recently been adding these sprints into my study routines and have seen tremendous amount of success. I always have these bing plans for my day but at the end of the evening, I NEVER get everything finished. This has really helped me buckle in and set goals for my study sessions. I get distracted somewhat easily but knowing after 90 minutes, I can take a 10-20 minute break after gets me through. Theres something that's so motivating about being timed that just works.

I really recommend trying Focus Sprints this week. Whether it's 60 minutes of focusing or only 25, it could really be the kick in pants you need to GET STUFF DONE.

Matt Howell | 3rd Year | Texarkana, TX üëÅ
‚ÄúFor me, optometry school has been a long lesson on the importance of perspective. Some things are simply a given: boring lectures, exhausting weeks, unfair exams, poorly organized assignments, bad professors, tough patients, ridiculous schedules, low grades, etc etc etc. You have NO control over those things. However, there‚Äôs one thing you DO have control over, your perspective. The lenses (pun intended) in which we view every moment is a CHOICE. You can choose to dread class/clinic every day (which is very easy to do). OR you can choose to recognize what a blessing it is to have the opportunity to become a doctor! Literally billions of people would kill to be in our positions and to learn the incredible things we learn. You could choose to be mad when a proctor gives excessively harsh feedback on your clinical skills. OR you could choose to see it as an opportunity to grow and improve. See what I‚Äôm getting at? Choose to be an opportunist, not a victim. I realize that this attitude towards life isn‚Äôt easy or even natural. But it‚Äôs worth it! What have you ever gained or accomplished through anxiety? Nothing. It‚Äôs a waste of your precious time and energy! Look for that silver lining in all situations and I promise that OD school can be fun.‚Äù

I love reading (obsessing) over productivity tips and goal settings, I've recently found: The best productivity hacks are in the questions you are not asking, sometimes they are right in your back pocket:
- What actions led to your biggest achievements last week?
- Can you repeat them this week?
- What seems to interrupt you every day?
- What distracted you the most yesterday?
- What were the intentions you set last week?
- Which of them did you get done? And why?
